WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:07.760
You're listening to TED Talks Daily, where we bring you new ideas to spark your curiosity

00:07.760 --> 00:08.760
every day.

00:08.760 --> 00:11.360
I'm your host, Elise Hugh.

00:11.360 --> 00:16.280
Screens have reshaped our lives in such profound ways that some days it feels like online happenings

00:16.280 --> 00:18.960
feel more real than real life.

00:18.960 --> 00:23.140
When we are together physically, we are each alone on our phones.

00:23.140 --> 00:26.760
But when we're in our phones, that's when we can be together.

00:26.760 --> 00:31.960
It's Naeema Raza, journalist, podcast host, and self-described dumb questions advocate.

00:31.960 --> 00:36.520
In today's talk, she questions how social media, digital life, and AI tools might be

00:36.520 --> 00:38.440
hijacking our lives.

00:38.440 --> 00:43.480
But instead of looking at the problem through an anti-tech lens, she looks at it with a

00:43.480 --> 00:45.440
pro-human one.

00:45.440 --> 00:50.720
It is sexy to think that the tech apocalypse is Arnold Schwarzenegger and the Terminator.

00:50.720 --> 00:53.160
But it could be so much more mundane than that.

00:53.160 --> 00:57.680
I want to make a case for old habits and tell you how I learned them the hard way.

00:57.680 --> 01:02.800
Naeema makes the case for the return of three practical habits to reconnect with that actually

01:02.800 --> 01:08.020
matter in our lives, both for ourselves and for younger generations.

01:08.020 --> 01:11.640
And stick around afterwards, I sat down with Naeema to go beyond her talk.

01:11.640 --> 01:17.240
We dig into why dumb questions are actually quite smart and why reigniting curiosity,

01:17.240 --> 01:22.680
restoring presence, and breaking free from our phones is more important now than ever.

01:22.680 --> 01:37.920
It's all coming up right after a short break from our sponsors.

01:37.920 --> 01:40.520
And now our TED Talk of the Day.

01:40.520 --> 01:49.000
I ask questions for a living to people like Mark Cuban, Neil deGrasse Tyson, Esther Perel,

01:49.000 --> 01:52.500
Bill Nye, these masters of their field.

01:52.500 --> 01:58.200
And the most surprising answer I heard this year was from two 11-year-olds named Sophie

01:58.200 --> 01:59.200
and Dylan.

01:59.200 --> 02:04.060
They too are experts in being kids these days.

02:04.060 --> 02:09.940
So I asked them, how does time with people on screens feel different than real life?

02:09.940 --> 02:14.820
It just makes you feel more like with them when you're on FaceTime.

02:14.820 --> 02:15.980
Even more than real life?

02:15.980 --> 02:21.980
Yeah, because you're like doing stuff together, like playing Roblox together.

02:21.980 --> 02:27.860
Because now, in days when you're with them, everyone's on their phones.

02:27.860 --> 02:30.900
Sophie's pointing out a profound paradox.

02:30.900 --> 02:35.080
When we are together physically, we are each alone on our phones.

02:35.080 --> 02:38.820
But when we're in our phones, that's when we can be together.

02:38.820 --> 02:41.560
The best way to not be distracted by your device?

02:41.560 --> 02:44.380
Just get inside of it.

02:44.380 --> 02:50.340
Now these 11-year-olds are not talking about some distant, anxious generation.

02:50.340 --> 02:52.380
They're talking about each of us.

02:52.380 --> 02:53.860
They're definitely talking about me.

02:53.860 --> 02:59.060
And about a world that's increasingly driven by machines.

02:59.060 --> 03:03.660
So I stumbled upon an extreme metaphor for what this could look like.

03:03.660 --> 03:05.700
And it's this guy who's locked in a Waymo.

03:05.700 --> 03:07.620
And it's driving him in circles.

03:07.620 --> 03:11.220
So he calls customer service and finds out he's not the only one trapped.

03:11.220 --> 03:13.860
Working with the situation of the vehicle.

03:13.860 --> 03:17.340
If you have your app pulled up, I need you to top my trip in the lower left corner of

03:17.340 --> 03:18.340
your app.

03:18.340 --> 03:19.340
Can't you just do it?

03:19.340 --> 03:21.340
You should be able to take over the car.

03:21.340 --> 03:24.020
You don't need my phone.

03:24.020 --> 03:26.340
I don't have an option.

03:26.340 --> 03:31.620
It is sexy to think that the tech apocalypse is Arnold Schwarzenegger and the Terminator.

03:31.620 --> 03:34.740
But it could be so much more mundane than that.

03:34.740 --> 03:40.100
Just us driven in circles, held hostage by drop-down menus.

03:40.100 --> 03:46.220
With gadgets disintermediating us from each other, from our own bodies, and from our curiosities.

03:46.220 --> 03:50.660
Because nowadays when we have a question, we don't wait and phone a friend.

03:50.660 --> 03:53.020
We friend our phones.

03:53.020 --> 03:57.700
And that feels so empowering to have all of this knowledge at our fingertips.

03:57.700 --> 04:03.500
Yet early research from MIT tells us it's making us lazier and less smart.

04:03.500 --> 04:06.780
And it is definitely making us less connected.

04:06.780 --> 04:10.780
This is not what our parents and grandparents were sold when they saw this relic of an ad

04:10.780 --> 04:14.740
from AT&T which says, reach out and touch someone.

04:14.740 --> 04:18.020
And yes, for all kinds of reasons, it would not go down well today.

04:18.020 --> 04:21.900
But it is oddly prescient.

04:21.900 --> 04:26.020
Because we have never been more connected and more out of touch.

04:26.020 --> 04:27.300
Now I'm not anti-tech.

04:27.300 --> 04:28.660
I actually cover it as a journalist.

04:28.660 --> 04:30.700
I have every gadget under the sun.

04:30.700 --> 04:34.300
And most days I think I'm in a relationship with my chat GPT.

04:34.300 --> 04:38.100
Or as I like to call him, chat daddy.

04:38.100 --> 04:40.100
I am pro human.

04:40.100 --> 04:46.180
And as we progress into an AI world that you've read 471.5 articles about today alone,

04:46.180 --> 04:48.700
I want to make a case for old habits.

04:48.700 --> 04:49.860
Three of them.

04:49.860 --> 04:52.580
And tell you how I learned them the hard way.

04:52.580 --> 04:54.540
The first is to pause.

04:54.540 --> 04:59.780
To take just one second when you feel that urge to reach for your digital pacifier.

04:59.780 --> 05:02.780
This by the way is a second.

05:02.780 --> 05:08.280
Studies show waiting that long before taking action lets your brain work better.

05:08.280 --> 05:10.200
The second is to wonder.

05:10.200 --> 05:13.920
Watch a movie without Googling who the actor is and what else is he in and how old is he

05:13.920 --> 05:14.920
in?

05:14.920 --> 05:15.920
Is he single?

05:15.920 --> 05:20.560
You can float in your own curiosity instead of drown in information.

05:20.560 --> 05:23.240
And the third is to ask a question.

05:23.240 --> 05:25.440
Out loud again.

05:25.440 --> 05:29.080
Have that fight at a dinner party instead of playing footsie with your phone.

05:29.080 --> 05:31.400
Ask something to someone you thought you couldn't learn from.

05:31.400 --> 05:34.920
Or someone you think you know everything about.

05:34.920 --> 05:39.080
Because the dumbest thing we can be is know it alls.

05:39.080 --> 05:42.480
A few years ago my father passed.

05:42.480 --> 05:46.000
And the days leading up to it I was glued to devices.

05:46.000 --> 05:48.280
They had all these answers.

05:48.280 --> 05:52.680
The number to his hospice nurse, how often to give the morphine, the signs to look out

05:52.680 --> 05:55.840
for, his heartbeat.

05:55.840 --> 06:01.520
But when he passed on a Sunday, a day before the data and the vitals suggested he would,

06:01.520 --> 06:03.240
that's when it hit me.

06:03.240 --> 06:06.400
The old habits for what mattered.

06:06.400 --> 06:10.600
Those seconds of pause that added up to minutes more.

06:10.600 --> 06:14.920
That weird and scary wonder about our own finite lives.

06:14.920 --> 06:21.880
And the little questions people ask me like, how can I be there for you?

06:21.880 --> 06:23.680
Sophie was on to something.

06:23.680 --> 06:25.200
But we're grownups.

06:25.200 --> 06:31.880
And we remember when presence and curiosity and connection were possible outside of technology.

06:31.880 --> 06:37.200
We have to practice these old habits if we hope to pass them on to a new generation.

06:37.200 --> 06:41.880
If we want to teach them how to be together when we are together.

06:41.880 --> 06:44.400
Right chat daddy?

06:44.400 --> 06:48.120
Thank you.

06:48.120 --> 06:49.120
Don't go away just yet.

06:49.120 --> 06:54.800
My conversation with Naiba is coming up right after a short break.

06:54.800 --> 07:00.800
Naiba, congratulations on your talk.

07:00.800 --> 07:02.280
Thank you so much, Elise.

07:02.280 --> 07:03.560
Really appreciate it.

07:03.560 --> 07:07.760
So for folks who don't know you, tell us just a little bit about yourself.

07:07.760 --> 07:10.040
What can I tell you?

07:10.040 --> 07:12.400
Well I'm very much my father's daughter.

07:12.400 --> 07:15.160
My dad was at the World Bank and so I grew up in all these places around the world.

07:15.160 --> 07:17.360
I grew up mostly in Africa and Asia.

07:17.360 --> 07:20.400
And largely being from places that I was not in.

07:20.400 --> 07:22.320
I was what's called a third culture kid.

07:22.320 --> 07:27.400
And I think that same kind of curiosity and fascination with the unknown has led me into

07:27.400 --> 07:32.400
my career which is what I do these days which is journalism and now independent journalism.

07:32.400 --> 07:34.160
I started off as a documentary filmmaker.

07:34.160 --> 07:39.280
I landed in journalism at the New York Times in the video section, the opinion video section.

07:39.280 --> 07:43.640
And then I ran a show called Sway which was hosted by the veteran tech journalist Cara

07:43.640 --> 07:44.640
Swisher.

07:44.640 --> 07:48.600
So cover technology was on air with her for another show.

07:48.600 --> 07:54.240
And then kind of left more institutional media about a year ago as I realized that you know

07:54.240 --> 07:57.280
so much of media is distrusted these days.

07:57.280 --> 08:01.640
It's really what brought me to this next arc and now I host a show called Smart Girl Dumb

08:01.640 --> 08:06.920
Questions and the idea is to you know ask questions as I recommend doing in the talk.

08:06.920 --> 08:08.520
Why do you call them dumb questions?

08:08.520 --> 08:12.320
Because it occurs to me that a lot of the questions that you ask that then become the

08:12.320 --> 08:16.680
fruits of conversation or more reporting are not dumb at all.

08:16.680 --> 08:18.760
They're just a starting point it sounds like.

08:18.760 --> 08:20.040
Yes, they're a starting point.

08:20.040 --> 08:21.840
I think it's more the ethos of the show.

08:21.840 --> 08:26.440
The title is decidedly provocative but I felt like it was a memorable title which is

08:26.440 --> 08:28.760
important when you title a show.

08:28.760 --> 08:36.560
And it gets to the idea and the idea is really about suspending certainty and inviting curiosity.

08:36.560 --> 08:41.240
And I think that this show does that and whether I'm asking you know Mark Cuban, can billionaires

08:41.240 --> 08:43.880
save us or Jeffrey Hinton, what even is AI?

08:43.880 --> 08:48.160
I mean that's a good example because Jeffrey Hinton who's the godfather of AI, I asked

08:48.160 --> 08:52.200
him do you think most people that interview you actually understand what AI is or how

08:52.200 --> 08:53.200
it works?

08:53.200 --> 08:54.200
He said no.

08:54.200 --> 08:57.520
Then I asked him do you think most people ask you to explain it to them and he said

08:57.520 --> 08:58.520
no.

08:58.520 --> 09:00.400
Huh, so you gave him an opportunity.

09:00.400 --> 09:02.040
Which I think is the questions we all have.

09:02.040 --> 09:03.040
Yeah.

09:03.040 --> 09:04.040
Yeah, absolutely.

09:04.040 --> 09:05.240
On to the talk.

09:05.240 --> 09:11.840
You started it with a story of these two 11 year olds who you had on your podcast and

09:11.840 --> 09:17.240
asked them how does time with people on screens feel different than time with people in real

09:17.240 --> 09:18.480
life?

09:18.480 --> 09:21.480
Why was their answer surprising to you?

09:21.480 --> 09:24.000
I mean wasn't it surprising to you Elise?

09:24.000 --> 09:30.640
It's shocking that they felt more present with people on screens than in real life.

09:30.640 --> 09:35.320
I mean it was a shocking answer but then when you think about it Sophie's explanation is

09:35.320 --> 09:37.400
so intelligent, right?

09:37.400 --> 09:40.680
When you're on screens you're doing stuff together, you're engaged with each other,

09:40.680 --> 09:43.920
but nowadays when you're together in real life everyone's just on their phones.

09:43.920 --> 09:48.960
I thought it was such a crisp cultural commentary by this 11 year old.

09:48.960 --> 09:54.000
And you made me really think about presence and the way that technology has changed presence

09:54.000 --> 09:57.440
and you know this isn't just about kids, this is about all of us.

09:57.440 --> 09:59.200
I feel that way with my friends too.

09:59.200 --> 10:03.320
When I'm on FaceTime there's no way to be distracted.

10:03.320 --> 10:04.320
That's true.

10:04.320 --> 10:09.080
Attention is such a finite resource and people are competing for it constantly and all the

10:09.080 --> 10:15.480
apps and industries are competing for ours and it makes even time in real life that sort

10:15.480 --> 10:18.000
of scarce resource.

10:18.000 --> 10:23.480
Do you feel like there is a generational shift of what it means to be connected?

10:23.480 --> 10:29.440
I don't always interview kids but when I speak to kids and I have four godkids and you know

10:29.440 --> 10:33.920
interact with friends kids and interviewed Sophie and Dylan, what I think is that they're

10:33.920 --> 10:36.000
much more cognizant of it.

10:36.000 --> 10:40.960
For them it's the world that they live in but when adults who are telling them one thing

10:40.960 --> 10:45.760
and doing another reveal themselves to be as connected to the technology as they want

10:45.760 --> 10:49.800
their kids not to be, I feel like yeah sure there's a generational shift but they seem

10:49.800 --> 10:52.320
more knowledgeable than us about the risks of it.

10:52.320 --> 10:57.080
I think it's very possible that fast forward 20 years we're going to look at these things,

10:57.080 --> 11:02.280
these screens, the way we looked at cigarettes and it might not be 20, it might be 5 to 10.

11:02.280 --> 11:06.880
When I say that not as some uninformed commentary but just as a journalist who's covered tech

11:06.880 --> 11:11.040
power and accountability that you look at the conversations that are happening right

11:11.040 --> 11:16.760
now in Capitol Hill etc. and the lawsuits that are ongoing, there's a real concern about

11:16.760 --> 11:22.680
how technology is impacting our lives in a way that we don't fully I think understand

11:22.680 --> 11:23.680
yet.

11:23.680 --> 11:27.800
Yeah and then the implications weren't considered when everybody was just getting onto the apps

11:27.800 --> 11:30.760
that then addicted us in the first place, right?

11:30.760 --> 11:37.960
So given this larger matrix that we're in, I also host a parenting podcast called Raising

11:37.960 --> 11:43.160
Us which is about how to talk about thorny topics with kids.

11:43.160 --> 11:48.720
So how would you approach talking about this larger system, this larger infrastructure

11:48.720 --> 11:54.120
that we're talking about that could be harmful with kids, with the teens that you're interviewing

11:54.120 --> 11:55.120
for example?

11:55.120 --> 12:00.520
Yeah, I mean I you know I'm not a parent yet so I feel I couldn't give parenting advice

12:00.600 --> 12:04.920
but I think it's about inquiry more than anything.

12:04.920 --> 12:09.880
You know I think it's much more revelatory when you interview people to ask them about

12:09.880 --> 12:12.800
their impacts and try to impose a perspective on them, right?

12:12.800 --> 12:16.680
I used to have this conversation with my former colleague Nick Kristoff at the New York Times

12:16.680 --> 12:21.640
where you know if you want to talk to someone about something like gun control, you don't

12:21.640 --> 12:23.160
start with an oppositional point of view.

12:23.160 --> 12:28.720
You ask them maybe what is a age that you think would make sense as a restricting age

12:28.720 --> 12:31.440
because I think 18 feels young.

12:31.440 --> 12:33.160
These are all the things you can't do at 18.

12:33.160 --> 12:37.120
And you engage in a conversation which shared space and I think if you ask people just how

12:37.120 --> 12:41.160
do you feel when you've spent an hour in technology and how do you look at it because what was

12:41.160 --> 12:45.440
revelatory to me and I think to the parents of those 11 year olds that I interviewed as

12:45.440 --> 12:49.360
well because they wrote this to me after is they hadn't really experienced their kids

12:49.360 --> 12:54.200
in that setting like adult interview subjects sharing the same kind of seat that Neil deGrasse

12:54.200 --> 12:58.960
Tyson or you know that the New York City mayor would share, right?

12:58.960 --> 13:02.920
And being asked questions in the same way of coming from a place of knowing.

13:02.920 --> 13:08.880
I think that that's how I would probably start is actually a mode of inquiry and then asking

13:08.880 --> 13:12.360
them like when do they otherwise feel really engaged and what I found with Sophie and Dylan

13:12.360 --> 13:15.280
is it's sports and I think about it to myself.

13:15.280 --> 13:16.280
It's swimming.

13:16.280 --> 13:17.920
When I swim, I grew up in Indonesia.

13:17.920 --> 13:23.640
I feel this like just complete joy of being free.

13:23.640 --> 13:25.000
You don't need any accoutrements.

13:25.000 --> 13:27.840
You're completely unplugged from the world.

13:27.840 --> 13:32.440
And so I think how do you create that sensation in people and then I studied economics undergrad

13:32.440 --> 13:37.840
and I'm always like thinking how do you create demand instead of just like push supply, you

13:37.840 --> 13:38.840
know?

13:38.840 --> 13:39.840
Yeah.

13:39.840 --> 13:42.440
Have you gotten to an answer for that question?

13:42.440 --> 13:45.960
I think it's really just taking that moment of cognizance to pause.

13:45.960 --> 13:48.960
I think it's the delight of not knowing something.

13:48.960 --> 13:52.640
We have conflated intelligence with knowing things with knowledge.

13:52.640 --> 13:56.080
I think intelligence, even the dictionary definition of intelligence, I believe is much

13:56.080 --> 14:01.880
more about the ability to learn and decide and shape your environment, adapt to it.

14:01.880 --> 14:06.800
I think there's even a higher node question which is like what do you want to learn about?

14:06.800 --> 14:07.800
That's curiosity.

14:07.800 --> 14:10.200
What are you willing to be open about?

14:10.200 --> 14:14.640
And that requires a confidence that I try to get to with a show title and smart girl

14:14.640 --> 14:15.880
down questions.

14:15.880 --> 14:16.880
Not certainty.

14:16.880 --> 14:17.880
It's the opposite of certainty.

14:17.880 --> 14:23.040
It's actually the ability to suspend knowledge to learn something from someone who you think

14:23.040 --> 14:25.600
you might not be able to learn from.

14:25.600 --> 14:29.520
And I think that is what's really missing and it kind of brings me back to the arc of

14:29.520 --> 14:31.800
my own trajectory in journalism.

14:31.800 --> 14:36.880
I think a lot of people, you look at the Gallup trust rankings which I think are at 28% right

14:36.880 --> 14:41.320
now of people who have a great deal or fair amount of trust in media.

14:41.320 --> 14:42.320
That's 28%.

14:42.320 --> 14:43.320
Wow.

14:43.320 --> 14:45.000
And I think that's what I think the reports of people do not.

14:45.000 --> 14:50.720
And I think that a lot of it is because people are being told what to think that the asking

14:50.720 --> 14:57.000
questions like the interrogative part of journalism has faded away and kind of been taken over

14:57.000 --> 15:01.800
by opinion journalism or hot takes or influencers are telling you what to think.

15:01.800 --> 15:03.840
And I think most people are like, I know how to think.

15:03.840 --> 15:07.120
I'd just like you to help me get information.

15:07.120 --> 15:14.320
And then what do you think is the connection between inquiry, being curious, wonder, and

15:14.320 --> 15:18.200
rebuilding trust or just maintaining connections with one another?

15:18.200 --> 15:20.160
I think you can't do one without the other, right?

15:20.160 --> 15:23.920
At least the connections and trust, they go hand in hand in a way.

15:23.920 --> 15:28.560
I think the act of curiosity and the act of being willing to be wrong or to not know or

15:28.560 --> 15:33.720
to learn creates like a physical space that I feel, oh, there's something between us that

15:33.720 --> 15:36.280
we can fill, we can learn together, right?

15:36.280 --> 15:41.680
And I think curiosity is like at the heart of that, not for play, not for show, but you're

15:41.680 --> 15:44.360
genuinely actually curious about something.

15:44.360 --> 15:46.360
And by the way, you could say, look, there are certain things I know.

15:46.360 --> 15:49.840
The sky is blue, the floor is down, whatever it is.

15:49.840 --> 15:53.500
But I guarantee you, there is something you can learn from somebody else.

15:53.500 --> 15:57.680
And if you ask a person a question, there are two things that happen, I think.

15:57.680 --> 16:01.740
One is you disarm that person to want to share something with you.

16:01.740 --> 16:05.160
The second is actually there's studies from, I think it was the University of California

16:05.160 --> 16:07.440
systems, I think it was a decade ago in 2014.

16:07.440 --> 16:11.240
They did some studies where they showed that when you're in a curiosity mindset, you're

16:11.240 --> 16:15.600
actually able to learn more and not just learn about the thing you're asking about or curious

16:15.600 --> 16:18.000
about, but learn all kinds of adjacencies.

16:18.000 --> 16:22.340
So you kind of build that plasticity and retain the ability to learn and who doesn't want

16:22.340 --> 16:23.500
to do that, right?

16:23.500 --> 16:26.880
So I think you change the other, you change yourself and you change the space between

16:26.880 --> 16:27.880
you.

16:27.880 --> 16:28.880
I love that.

16:28.880 --> 16:35.880
What do you think then if curiosity and asking questions can be so connective and so good,

16:35.880 --> 16:40.360
not only on a one-to-one basis, but just for society as a whole, why do you think we are

16:40.360 --> 16:44.920
so afraid to ask or worried about asking dumb questions?

16:44.920 --> 16:48.480
Well, one, I think that we all have like a, you know, Polly Pocket.

16:48.480 --> 16:50.760
I'm holding up my phone right now for people listening.

16:50.760 --> 16:53.920
You know, I think that we can just ask our phone.

16:53.920 --> 16:57.440
And you know, a dinner party game I like to play is like, would you rather have someone

16:57.440 --> 17:04.120
see your texts, your emails or all of your search or chat history?

17:04.120 --> 17:08.680
And often people are very worried about their texts and their search and chat history.

17:08.680 --> 17:11.840
I would say it's like the, I think they're revealing.

17:11.840 --> 17:16.520
I think if you've ever seen somebody's search history on accident, I remembered.

17:16.520 --> 17:17.520
What would you rather?

17:17.520 --> 17:19.280
Oh, I'm really open.

17:19.280 --> 17:21.880
I feel like my search history is probably hilarious.

17:21.880 --> 17:24.640
So I don't, I don't, I wouldn't feel exposed about that.

17:24.640 --> 17:30.360
Probably my texts, probably my texts because any of my, my judgey conversations are probably

17:30.360 --> 17:31.360
in there.

17:31.360 --> 17:35.560
And your curious conversations are in your chat.

17:35.560 --> 17:36.560
Yeah.

17:36.560 --> 17:39.960
I mean, I think that that, you know, the technology has shifted our ability to ask questions and

17:39.960 --> 17:45.360
to know things and to be quote unquote experts and to therefore, revile experts is become

17:45.360 --> 17:48.240
much more practice with this new medium.

17:48.240 --> 17:52.800
I also think that we conflate it with a weakness, not knowing.

17:52.800 --> 17:53.800
Right.

17:53.800 --> 17:57.440
And what I do at the end of every episode of Smart Girl Done Questions, I ask my guests

17:57.440 --> 17:58.440
what they do not know.

17:58.440 --> 18:02.080
And these are extremely smart people, experts in their field.

18:02.080 --> 18:03.160
And I asked them what they don't know.

18:03.160 --> 18:05.520
And they're, they have hilarious answers.

18:05.520 --> 18:09.040
Jeffrey Hinton, the Godfather of AI said, he still doesn't really understand what his

18:09.040 --> 18:11.720
life's work has been, how the brain really works.

18:11.720 --> 18:15.920
You know, what a vulnerable answer to share something like that.

18:15.920 --> 18:19.400
And cause I love that space of not knowing.

18:19.400 --> 18:20.400
Right.

18:20.400 --> 18:21.600
It really is delightful.

18:21.600 --> 18:26.160
And I think it's that space for play that we just have in spades as kids that Sophie

18:26.160 --> 18:31.920
and Dylan still have at 11 that we really lose as adults.

18:31.920 --> 18:35.040
Not because we're not curious, not because we're not able to be curious, not because

18:35.040 --> 18:40.400
we're not intelligent, but because we simply stop noticing because there is a more expedient

18:40.400 --> 18:45.600
way to know something and because it appears strong to know something.

18:45.600 --> 18:50.280
But everyone thinks the person in the conversation who raises their hand, like in a meeting and

18:50.280 --> 18:51.760
says like, what does that acronym mean?

18:51.760 --> 18:53.360
And you're like, oh my God, thank God.

18:53.360 --> 18:55.480
Cause everyone's thinking it.

18:55.480 --> 18:56.480
It's a public service.

18:56.480 --> 18:58.480
It's like public service journalism 101.

18:58.480 --> 18:59.480
Yeah.

18:59.480 --> 19:00.480
Yeah.

19:00.480 --> 19:01.480
That's so great.

19:01.480 --> 19:04.240
What's the next question that you're excited to explore?

19:04.240 --> 19:07.000
Do you think that the future of humanity is cyborg?

19:07.000 --> 19:09.720
And it's a question that I've asked to various of my guests.

19:09.720 --> 19:13.440
I think I'm fascinated by this idea of transhumanism.

19:13.440 --> 19:18.400
I'm not like a believer in this necessarily, but I'm very curious about how, you know,

19:18.400 --> 19:24.040
the machines, the phones, et cetera, will actually change in form to be integrated with

19:24.040 --> 19:25.040
us.

19:25.040 --> 19:28.800
What does the future of that look like as we're experimenting with wearables, with, you

19:28.800 --> 19:31.240
know, lenses, with all kinds of things?

19:31.240 --> 19:37.240
And you know, you have people like Alexander Wang, who runs AI at META, who says he's waiting

19:37.240 --> 19:42.600
to have kids until the neural link is so far advanced that we can just plug our babies

19:42.600 --> 19:47.360
into neural link and they can, you know, digest information at a point at which they're most

19:47.360 --> 19:48.360
neuroplastic.

19:48.360 --> 19:50.720
Like, there is a school of thought.

19:50.720 --> 19:56.720
It sounds absurd and like science fiction, but I think it's not impossible.

19:56.720 --> 20:02.080
So that's my great curiosity is like, what are we, you know, fast forward two generations,

20:02.080 --> 20:07.280
you know, removing from homo erectus to homo machinists or whatever the right term would

20:07.280 --> 20:08.280
be.

20:08.280 --> 20:09.280
Yeah.

20:09.280 --> 20:10.280
Yeah.

20:10.280 --> 20:11.280
Well, that's a good one.

20:11.280 --> 20:12.600
I still want to know where Jimmy Hoffa is buried.

20:12.600 --> 20:15.600
Oh, that's a good one.

20:15.600 --> 20:19.080
You know, I also want to know like why some people like spicy food and other people do

20:19.080 --> 20:20.080
not.

20:20.080 --> 20:21.420
That's a good one.

20:21.420 --> 20:24.120
Can you learn to like spicy food?

20:24.120 --> 20:26.800
People who sort of have never been exposed to it.

20:26.800 --> 20:27.800
Is it acquired?

20:27.800 --> 20:34.720
As a Pakistani who has dated some men from the Midwest, I would say that hard to acquire,

20:34.720 --> 20:36.800
but you can encourage that behavior.

20:36.800 --> 20:37.800
Really?

20:37.800 --> 20:38.800
Interesting.

20:38.800 --> 20:39.800
Yeah.

20:39.800 --> 20:40.800
Interesting.

20:40.800 --> 20:41.800
All right.

20:41.800 --> 20:42.800
I've learned so much from you.

20:42.800 --> 20:45.560
Before we let you go, real briefly, Naima, what do you hope people will enjoy?

20:45.560 --> 20:51.960
What will learn, feel, and do after listening to this talk and conversation?

20:51.960 --> 20:55.920
I hope they will feel empowered and I hope they will fight at the dinner table.

20:55.920 --> 21:00.640
I hope they will have conversations out loud again and ask the question and get into it

21:00.640 --> 21:05.880
in conversation versus on their screen.

21:05.880 --> 21:08.960
Fantastic.

21:08.960 --> 21:14.700
That was Naima Raza at TEDNEX 2025 and in conversation with me, Elise Hugh.

